      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion earlier. Let's dive straight into the technical side of how a blockage in a pitot tube affects the pressure reading, without any goblin references this time.\n\nWhen a pitot tube experiences a blockage, such as from ice or debris, the airflow into the tube is restricted. This restriction leads to a buildup of pressure inside the tube because the air cannot escape as freely as it would under normal conditions. The pitot tube measures the difference between the static pressure (the air pressure around the aircraft) and the total pressure (the pressure inside the pitot tube, which includes the dynamic pressure from the airflow).\n\nUnder normal conditions, the total pressure inside the pitot tube is slightly higher than the static pressure due to the dynamic pressure from the moving air. This pressure difference is what the airspeed indicator uses to calculate the aircraft's airspeed.\n\nHowever, when there's a blockage, the total pressure inside the pitot tube increases because the restricted airflow cannot equalize the pressure difference as effectively. This results in a higher total pressure reading. The airspeed indicator, which calculates airspeed based on the difference between the total and static pressures, will then interpret this incorrect pressure difference as a lower airspeed than the aircraft is actually flying.",
